<subSubSection id="C3606517B7BCFF0965E97BD6DF08F873" pageId="237" pageNumber="238" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC5369CB7BCFF0965E97BD6DDE0F965" blockId="237.[189,400,1764,1790]" box="[189,400,1764,1790]" pageId="237" pageNumber="238">
<heading id="D08D81F0B7BCFF0965E97BD6DDE0F965" bold="true" box="[189,400,1764,1790]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="237" pageNumber="238" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8EB7BCFF0965E97BD6DDE0F965" bold="true" box="[189,400,1764,1790]" pageId="237" pageNumber="238">Brief description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC5369CB7BCFF0965E97A26DF08F873" blockId="237.[189,1399,1812,2025]" pageId="237" pageNumber="238">Monoecious. Receptacle three-celled. Cells I and II separated by an oblique septum. Cell III in contact with cell I and to a certain extent with cell VI. Primary appendage free, consisting of several superposed cells, each (except for the basal cell) giving rise to 1–2 lateral antheridia, where the uppermost bears a dorsal spinous process (the original spore apex, sx). Perithecium with four cells in each vertical row of outer wall cells; the perithecial tip bears a complex of subapical and apical lobes. Trichogyne two-celled, consisting of a basal cell bearing one apically papillate cell.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3606517B7BFFF0A65E97C3BDE91FDAD" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC5369CB7BFFF0A65E97C3BDD5FFEB8" blockId="238.[189,303,265,291]" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">
<heading id="D08D81F0B7BFFF0A65E97C3BDD5FFEB8" bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8EB7BFFF0A65E97C3BDD5FFEB8" bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC5369CB7BFFF0A65E97C08DE91FDAD" blockId="238.[189,1399,314,566]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">
The genus consists of ten species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B6DB7BFFF0A671F7C08DE8FFECF" author="Das K. &amp; Rossi W. &amp; Leonardi M." box="[587,767,314,340]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" pagination="381 - 418" refId="ref211448" refString="Das K., Rossi W., Leonardi M., et al. 2018. Fungal Biodiversity Profiles 61 - 70. CrYptogamie, MYcologie 39 (4): 381 - 418. https: // doi. org / 10.7872 / crym / v 39. iss 4.2018.381" type="journal article" year="2018">
Das 
<emphasis id="B90EEA8EB7BFFF0A672B7C08DEC9FECF" box="[639,697,314,340]" italics="true" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
), of which three in Europe, two in 
<collectingCountry id="F36D760CB7BFFF0A61DB7C08D970FECF" box="[1167,1280,314,340]" name="Denmark" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">Denmark</collectingCountry>
. The most recently described species is 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1FB7BFFF0A675D7C52D879FEE2" authority="(Haelewaters &amp; De Kesel 2020)" baseAuthorityName="Haelewaters &amp; De Kesel" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[521,1033,351,378]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Hesperomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="halyziae">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8EB7BFFF0A675D7C52DEFCFEE2" box="[521,652,351,377]" italics="true" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">H. halyziae</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B6DB7BFFF0A67CE7C6DD871FEE2" author="Haelewaters D. &amp; De Kesel A." box="[666,1025,351,378]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" pagination="23 - 86" refId="ref213175" refString="Haelewaters D. &amp; De Kesel A. 2020. Checklist of thallus - forming Laboulbeniomycetes from Belgium and the Netherlands, including Hesperomyces halyziae and Laboulbenia quarantenae spp. nov. MycoKeys 71: 23 - 86. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / mycokeys. 71.53421" type="journal article" year="2020">Haelewaters &amp; De Kesel 2020</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This is perhaps one of the most studied and recorded genera in the laboulbenialean literature, especially concerning the mostly frequent species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1FB7BFFF0A64767C9EDEECFE5E" authority="Thaxt." authorityName="Thaxt." box="[290,668,427,453]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Hesperomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="virescens">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8EB7BFFF0A64767C9EDE32FE5E" box="[290,578,428,453]" italics="true" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">Hesperomyces virescens</emphasis>
Thaxt.
</taxonomicName>
, well-studied both under SEM and light microscopy (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B6DB7BFFF0A60487C99DD26FE77" author="Weir A. &amp; Beakes G. W." pageId="238" pageNumber="239" pagination="677 - 693" refId="ref224096" refString="Weir A. &amp; Beakes G. W. 1996. Correlative light- and scanning electron microscope studies on the developmental morphology of Hesperomyces virescens. Mycologia 88 (5): 677 - 693. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3760962" type="journal article" year="1996">Weir &amp; Beakes 1996</bibRefCitation>
), one of the first 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1FB7BFFF0A67437CE3DEBAFE70" authorityName="Lindau" authorityYear="1898" box="[535,714,465,491]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="order">Laboulbeniales</taxonomicName>
to be sequenced (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B6DB7BFFF0A66CC7CE3D8C2FE70" author="Weir A. &amp; Blackwell M." box="[920,1202,465,491]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" pagination="802 - 806" refId="ref224142" refString="Weir A. &amp; Blackwell M. 2001. Extraction and PCR amplification of DNA from minute ectoparasitic fungi. Mycologia 93 (4): 802 - 806. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00275514.2001.12063212" type="journal article" year="2001">Weir &amp; Blackwell 2001</bibRefCitation>
), and intensively reported and studied because of its presence on the invasive coccinellid beetle, the harlequin ladybird 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1FB7BFFF0A65E97F2FDEACFDAD" authority="(Garces &amp; Williams 2004)" baseAuthorityName="Garces &amp; Williams" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[189,732,540,566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Harmonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="axyridis">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8EB7BFFF0A65E97F2FDDECFDAD" box="[189,412,540,566]" italics="true" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">Harmonia axyridis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B6DB7BFFF0A64FF7F2EDEA5FDAD" author="Garces S. &amp; Williams R." box="[427,725,540,566]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" pagination="156 - 158" refId="ref212724" refString="Garces S. &amp; Williams R. 2004. First record of Hesperomyces virescens Thaxter (Laboulbeniales: Ascomycetes) on Harmonia axyridis (Pallas) (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society 77 (2): 156 - 158. https: // doi. org / 10.2317 / 0304.18.1" type="journal article" year="2004">Garces &amp; Williams 2004</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3606517B7BFFF0A65E97F52DF8DFDE1" box="[189,1021,608,634]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" type="multiple">
<paragraph id="8BC5369CB7BFFF0A65E97F52DF8DFDE1" blockId="238.[189,1021,608,634]" box="[189,1021,608,634]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">
